<TITLE> Psychiatrist and broadcaster Anthony Clare dies </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 DUBLIN, Oct 30 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Psychiatrist, broadcaster and author Professor Anthony Clare has died at the age of 64, Irish media reported on Tuesday. Clare, best known as the presenter of BBC Radio 4's series "In The Psychiatrist's Chair", died in Paris at the weekend, two months before he was due to retire from his post at an acute psychiatric unit near Dublin, the Irish Times reported. "He was not only the best known psychiatrist in Ireland and Britain, but in the United States as well because he made regular trips there," Patricia Casey, professor of psychiatry at Dublin's Mater Misericordiae Hospital, told RTE radio. "He did indeed demystify psychiatry at a time when people thought that psychiatrists had two horns and locked people up," Casey said of a man who also co-wrote the book "Depression and how to survive it" with comedian Spike Millig
